{"workspaceId": "documentation-project-gamma", "sessionId": "doc-s2947-alpha", "memory": "Drafting documentation for new Authentication API endpoints with code examples.", "goal": "Document the new Authentication API endpoints with code examples in Python and JavaScript.", "constraints": "Preserve surrounding content and do not modify unrelated files.", "tool": "content write "Authentication/New Authentication Endpoints.md" "---
title: New Authentication Endpoints
description: Documentation for the newly released authentication endpoints.
tags: [authentication, API, endpoints, security]
aliases: [New Authentication API]
category: documentation
---

## Introduction

This document details the newly released authentication endpoints for our platform. These endpoints provide enhanced security and flexibility for user authentication. This documentation covers the purpose of each endpoint, required parameters, and example usage with Python and JavaScript code examples.

## Prerequisites

*   A valid API key.
*   Familiarity with RESTful API concepts.
*   Python 3.6+ installed.
*   Node.js 12+ installed.

## Endpoints

### 1. `/auth/register`

This endpoint allows new users to register an account.

**Method:** `POST`

**Request Body:**

```json
{
  \"username\": \"newuser\",
  \"password\": \"securepassword\",
  \"email\": \"newuser@example.com\"
}
```

**Response:**

```json
{
  \"status\": \"success\",
  \"message\": \"User registered successfully.\"
}
```

**Python Example:**

```python
import requests
import json

url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/register\"
headers = {\"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"}
data = {\"username\": \"newuser\", \"password\": \"securepassword\", \"email\": \"newuser@example.com\"}

response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=json.dumps(data))

print(response.json())
```

**JavaScript Example:**

```javascript
const axios = require('axios');

const url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/register\";
const data = { username: \"newuser\", password: \"securepassword\", email: \"newuser@example.com\" };

axios.post(url, data)
  .then(response => {
    console.log(response.data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

### 2. `/auth/login`

This endpoint allows users to log in and obtain an authentication token.

**Method:** `POST`

**Request Body:**

```json
{
  \"username\": \"existinguser\",
  \"password\": \"securepassword\"
}
```

**Response:**

```json
{
  \"status\": \"success\",
  \"token\": \"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...\"
}
```

**Python Example:**

```python
import requests
import json

url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/login\"
headers = {\"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"}
data = {\"username\": \"existinguser\", \"password\": \"securepassword\"}

response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=json.dumps(data))

print(response.json())
```

**JavaScript Example:**

```javascript
const axios = require('axios');

const url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/login\";
const data = { username: \"existinguser\", password: \"securepassword\" };

axios.post(url, data)
  .then(response => {
    console.log(response.data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

### 3. `/auth/validate`

This endpoint validates an authentication token.

**Method:** `POST`

**Request Header:**

```
Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

**Response:**

```json
{
  \"status\": \"success\",
  \"message\": \"Token is valid.\"
}
```

**Python Example:**

```python
import requests

url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/validate\"
headers = {\"Authorization\": \"Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...\"}

response = requests.post(url, headers=headers)

print(response.json())
```

**JavaScript Example:**

```javascript
const axios = require('axios');

const url = \"https://api.example.com/auth/validate\";
const headers = { Authorization: `Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...` };

axios.post(url, null, { headers: headers })
  .then(response => {
    console.log(response.data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

## Troubleshooting

> [!warning]
> **Invalid Credentials:**  If you receive an \"Invalid credentials\" error, double-check your username and password.

> [!tip]
> **Token Expiration:**  Authentication tokens have a limited lifespan. Ensure you refresh your token regularly using the appropriate refresh token endpoint (not covered in this initial documentation).

## Security Considerations

*   Always store authentication tokens securely.
*   Implement proper input validation to prevent injection attacks.
*   Use HTTPS to encrypt all communication with the API.
""}

{"workspaceId": "documentation-project-alpha", "sessionId": "doc-s2-09282024", "memory": "User wants a tutorial on customizing the user interface for developers familiar with React.", "goal": "Write a tutorial on UI customization with React.", "constraints": "Preserve surrounding content and do not modify unrelated files.", "tool": "content write "Advanced Topics/Customization.md" "---
title: Customizing the User Interface with React
description: A tutorial for developers on customizing the user interface using React components.
tags: [customization, UI, React, components]
aliases: [UI Customization, React UI]
category: \"documentation\"
---

## Introduction

This tutorial guides developers familiar with React on how to customize the user interface components. We will cover overriding default styles, creating custom components, and integrating them into the existing application.

## Prerequisites

*   Basic knowledge of React and JSX.
*   Node.js and npm installed.
*   A working development environment.

## Step 1: Understanding the Component Structure

Before customizing, it's crucial to understand the current component structure. Use the React DevTools to inspect the component tree and identify the components you want to modify.

## Step 2: Overriding Default Styles

You can override the default styles using CSS classes. For example, let's say you want to change the background color of a button component:

1.  Locate the CSS class associated with the button component (e.g., `.my-button`).
2.  Create a new CSS file or use an existing one.
3.  Override the style properties:

    ```css
    .my-button {
      background-color: #007bff !important; /* Use !important to ensure your style overrides the default */
      color: white;
      border: none;
      padding: 10px 20px;
    }
    ```

4.  Import the CSS file in your main application file.

## Step 3: Creating Custom Components

For more complex customizations, you might need to create custom components. Here's an example of creating a custom input field:

1.  Create a new React component file (e.g., `CustomInputField.js`):

    ```jsx
    import React from 'react';

    const CustomInputField = ({ label, value, onChange }) => {
      return (
        <div>
          <label>{label}</label>
          <input type=\"text\" value={value} onChange={onChange} />
        </div>
      );
    };

    export default CustomInputField;
    ```

2.  Import and use the custom component in your application:

    ```jsx
    import React, { useState } from 'react';
    import CustomInputField from './CustomInputField';

    const MyComponent = () => {
      const [inputValue, setInputValue] = useState('');

      const handleInputChange = (event) => {
        setInputValue(event.target.value);
      };

      return (
        <CustomInputField
          label=\"Enter your name:\"
          value={inputValue}
          onChange={handleInputChange}
        />
      );
    };

    export default MyComponent;
    ```

## Step 4: Integrating Custom Components

To integrate the custom component, you need to replace the existing component with your new one. Ensure that you pass the necessary props and handle events correctly.

## Step 5: Using Configuration Files

> [!tip] Using a configuration file to define UI variations without affecting core components.

For more advanced customization without directly modifying core components, you can use configuration files (e.g., JSON) to define properties that get used by the component:

```json
// config.json
{
  \"buttonColor\": \"#007bff\",
  \"textColor\": \"white\"
}
```

Then load this configuration in your React component and use it to style or configure the component as needed.

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import config from './config.json';

const ConfigurableButton = () => {
  const [buttonStyle, setButtonStyle] = useState({});

  useEffect(() => {
    setButtonStyle({
      backgroundColor: config.buttonColor,
      color: config.textColor
    });
  }, []);

  return (
    <button style={buttonStyle}>Click Me</button>
  );
};

export default ConfigurableButton;
```

## Troubleshooting

*   **Styles not overriding:** Ensure you're using `!important` in your CSS or that your CSS file is loaded after the default styles.
*   **Component not rendering:** Check for errors in your component code using the browser console and React DevTools.
*   **Props not being passed correctly:** Verify the props you're passing to the custom component match the expected types and names.

## Conclusion

Customizing the user interface with React involves understanding the component structure, overriding default styles, creating custom components, and integrating them effectively. By following these steps, you can create a unique and personalized user experience.
