title: Authentication
description: Learn how to authenticate with our API.
tags: [authentication, api, security]
aliases: [auth, login, security]
category: documentation
---

## Authentication Overview

This document provides a comprehensive guide to authenticating with our API. Proper authentication is crucial for accessing protected resources and ensuring the security of your data. We support API key authentication, detailed below.

### Prerequisites

*   An active account with our service. If you don't have one, you can sign up [here](example.com/signup).
*   Familiarity with making HTTP requests using tools like `curl`, `Postman`, or programming languages like Python or JavaScript.

## API Key Authentication

The most common method of authentication is using an API key. You can obtain your API key from your account dashboard under the \"API Keys\" section.

### Obtaining an API Key

1.  Log in to your account at [example.com/login](example.com/login).
2.  Navigate to the \"API Keys\" section in your account settings.
3.  Click the \"Generate New API Key\" button.
4.  Copy the generated API key.  **Keep this key secure!** It's like a password.

### Using the API Key

To authenticate your API requests, include the `X-API-Key` header with your API key value.

**Example using curl:**

```bash
curl -H \"X-API-Key: YOUR_API_KEY\" https://api.example.com/resource
```

**Example using Python:**

```python
import requests

api_key = \"YOUR_API_KEY\"
headers = {
    \"X-API-Key\": api_key
}

response = requests.get(\"https://api.example.com/resource\", headers=headers)

if response.status_code == 200:
    print(response.json())
else:
    print(f\"Error: {response.status_code} - {response.text}\")
```

**Example using JavaScript (Node.js):**

```javascript
const https = require('https');

const apiKey = 'YOUR_API_KEY';

const options = {
  hostname: 'api.example.com',
  path: '/resource',
  method: 'GET',
  headers: {
    'X-API-Key': apiKey
  }
};

const req = https.request(options, (res) => {
  let data = '';

  res.on('data', (chunk) => {
    data += chunk;
  });

  res.on('end', () => {
    console.log(JSON.parse(data));
  });
}).on(\"error\", (err) => {
  console.log(\"Error: \", err.message);
});

req.end();
```

> [!tip]
> Always store your API key securely and never expose it in client-side code or public repositories.

## Troubleshooting

### Invalid API Key

If you receive a `401 Unauthorized` error, it likely indicates an invalid or missing API key. Double-check that you've included the correct API key in the `X-API-Key` header.

### API Key Permissions

Your API key may not have the necessary permissions to access certain resources. Review the API key's permissions in your account dashboard and ensure it has the required access.

### Rate Limiting

To prevent abuse, we enforce rate limits on our API. If you exceed the rate limit, you'll receive a `429 Too Many Requests` error. Refer to the rate limiting documentation for more information.

## Rotating API Keys

It’s a good security practice to periodically rotate your API keys. To rotate your API key:

1.  Generate a new API key.
2.  Update your application to use the new API key.
3.  Deactivate the old API key. This will prevent it from being used to access the API.

> [!warning]
> Deactivating an API key will immediately prevent it from being used. Ensure your application is updated with the new API key before deactivating the old one.

### API Key Security Best Practices

*   **Never commit your API key to version control systems.** Use environment variables or secure configuration management tools to store your API key.
*   **Restrict API key permissions.** Grant your API key only the necessary permissions to access the resources your application needs.
*   **Monitor API key usage.** Regularly monitor your API key usage to detect any suspicious activity.
*   **Implement rate limiting.** Protect your API from abuse by implementing rate limiting.

## Further Reading

*   [API Key Management](example.com/api-key-management)
*   [Rate Limiting](example.com/rate-limiting)

